        <page n="01" image="pa.fr.vs.1860.10.17.01">
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>Why Breckinridge Should Be Supported</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Describes the reasons Breckinridge should be elected. These include:
                    because he isn't an office seeker, because he isn't politically inconsistent,
                    and because he is a national, not sectional, Democrat.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="table">
                <column>02-04</column>
                <head>Franklin County--Official Returns of the Election held October 17, 1860</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Official returns of the local and state elections. Foster and Schell were
                    both defeated.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look>Look</look>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>03</column>
                <head>The Beginning of the End</head>
                <origin>Pittsburg Dispatch</origin>
                <commentary>The article "speaks for itself, and carries with it its own comments."</commentary>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The Wide Awakes ask the men of Pittsburgh to form a Wide Awake Club "for
                    the purpose of furthering the interests of the friend of the human race, Abraham
                    Lincoln."</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>03</column>
                <head>Political Lecture by a Pious Wife</head>
                <origin>Buffalo Republic</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Satirical argument between a wife and her husband, who is a Wide Awake.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>04</column>
                <head>Southern and Northern Exports</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Quotes export statistics to show the "relative degrees of commercial
                    affinity between the North and the South."</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>05</column>
                <head>Who Seceded</head>
                <origin>Capital City Fact</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Asserts that Stephen A. Douglas "seceded from the Constitution of the
                    United States, which guarantees rights to all States."</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>06</column>
                <head>Fairly and Well Put</head>
                <origin>New York Day Book</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Asks the commercial men of New York, who claim to be Republicans, if they
                    really support the radical doctrines of William Seward.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>06</column>
                <head>Douglas Now and Then</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Compares two contradictory statements by Douglas on the subject of Kansas
                    and Dred Scott. In 1857, he stated that the Court decision was binding. At
                    Freeport, he claimed that the citizens of a territory could legally exclude
                    slavery.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>06</column>
                <head>Rage of the Douglas Men in Ohio</head>
                <origin>Indianapolis Guard</origin>
                <commentary>"It looks as if the Douglasites were losing their temper at the prospect
                    of annihilation."</commentary>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Quotes from Douglas supporters that insult Breckinridge.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>06</column>
                <head>Increase of Slaves in Missouri</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The increasing number of slaves in Missouri gives lie to the free-soil
                    assertion that slavery is dying out in that state.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
