        <page n="04" image="pa.fr.vs.1860.10.17.04">
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>The Result</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The Spirit is surprised and saddened by the defeat of the Democrats in the
                    state and local elections. It blames these defeats on the treachery of the
                    straight-out Douglas faction led by Forney.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>02</column>
                <head>Converts to Republicanism</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The Transcript announced that D. Watson Rowe and Wm. S. Everett had
                    deserted the Democratic Party and joined the Republicans. This didn't surprise
                    the Spirit because they "followed straight-out Douglasism to its logical
                    conclusion."</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>03</column>
                <head>Forney Straight Out for McClure</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Accuses the straight-out supporters of having cut a number of deals that
                    will provide them with positions in return for their support.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>03</column>
                <head>Swindling their Friends</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Accuses Forney, Haldeman, and Lauman of benefiting greatly as a result of
                    Curtin's election.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>03</column>
                <head>The Election Returns</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Curtin won the state by a roughly 30,000 vote majority. Austin won in the
                    legislative district by 400 votes. McPherson was re-elected to Congress by 400
                    votes.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>04</column>
                <head>Douglas Deception</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Insists that Douglas is not really the regular nominee, since he didn't
                    gain enough votes at the convention, and that Breckinridge is not the secession
                    candidate.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>05</column>
                <head>Who Support Breckinridge and Lane</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>A list of prominent Democrats, including Buchanan, from all across the
                    country who support Breckinridge.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>06</column>
                <head>Democratic State Committee</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The State Committee met at Reading and rescinded the Cresson resolution.
                    The Committee decided to support the Reading Electoral ticket instead.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote/>
        </page>
        <page n="05" image="pa.fr.vs.1860.10.17.05">
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>The Press and the Times</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Accuses the Times of sympathizing and acting in conjunction with Forney,
                    Haldeman, and Lauman.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="l">
                <column>02</column>
                <head>Letter From Virginia</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Letter from a man who was born in Franklin County and lives in Charlestown,
                    Virginia. He is pleased with the Spirit's decision to support Breckinridge and
                    claims that Douglas has no support in the South. He also states that the South
                    has a defensive position and that Virginia and Pennsylvania should have
                    identical views toward slavery.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
